 :tx/rationale "AUDIT-EXT TYPE-9 (from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT Section 8): The deepest question — is the system observing its own failure to converge? PROBLEM: The project's bedrock claim is that it implements observe-compare-reduce at every level. But the system's most important discrepancy — F(S) stagnant at 0.62 for 13 sessions, hypothesis ledger degrading, 265 untested INVs accumulating — is not being detected, diagnosed, or reduced by the system itself. A human reading the dashboard sees these numbers. But: does the guidance system emit 'your verification pipeline is the bottleneck'? Does the routing function prioritize verification tasks over new feature tasks when the spec-impl gap is widening? Does the harvest capture 'F(S) hasn't moved in 5 sessions — this is anomalous'? JUSTIFICATION: If Braid is truly a learning system, it should detect its own stagnation as Type 9 divergence (Reflexive: system vs system's-model-of-itself) and recommend the verification sprint that the external assessment recommends. If it can't — if it takes an external audit to identify the obvious — then the self-improvement loop (the Y-combinator property from session-038) isn't yet operational. The test: run 'braid status' and 'braid seed --task improve convergence' and see if the system recommends what this assessment recommends. SOLUTION: This is not a code fix — it is a fitness function enhancement. F(S) stagnation over N sessions should trigger an anomaly detection signal. The guidance routing should detect when the spec-impl gap is widening and prioritize verification over new features. VERIFICATION: braid seed --task 'improve convergence' recommends verification sprint without human intervention. DEPENDENCIES: Requires calibration fix, coverage bug fix, and verification sprint to validate. This is the meta-level test of whether the system works. FINDING SOURCE: PROJECT_ASSESSMENT.md Section 8. SEVERITY: Critical (existential)."
